h Ex.\r\n* Likeliness of both partners being the same \"place\" is low, so there are expectations.  \r\n* Notion of friendship is broad spectrum: all the way from BFFs to just not hating each other.  \r\n* On the friend spectrum vs. the friend zone.\r\n* How do we solve kind of friends we are?  \r\n   -> Flavour terminology as an analogy towards improving our vocabulary of types of friendships that are possible.  \r\n* Not a good feedback loop for what did and did not work in a relationship.  \r\n* Easier to get feedback from friends, but harder from ex partners.\r\n* Luke suggests exit interviews.  Heidi suggests have feedback meetings more frequently.  \r\n* Focus empathetically on the other partner in a relationship.  \r\n* Heidi implies that positive feedback and affirmation is under-appreciated in arguments and relationship discussions.  Also makes the hard stuff easier to take.  \r\n* Kris spent several years on Facebag as a warrior for technical correctness, but now realizes that most people don\'t want it.  \r\n   * Should there be a badge for who does and who does not want technical correctness.  \r\n   * Heidi suggests asking people what sort of feedback they want.  \r\n* Luke: is non-violent communication what we need?  \r\n   * Kris found it fatiguing, but that was in a poly relationship that had a _lot_ of communication.  \r\n* Kris wants feedback and critique on whatever.  \r\n* What\'s the line?  Where does criticism become misanthropic?  \r\n* Heidi: there are ways to communicate in a caring and helpful/non-misanthropic way?  \r\n* Luke: autism spectrum people have a hard time grasping social queues, and therefore communicating healthily.   \r\n* Aspergers no longer is a diagnosis.\r\n* Night owls are more creative and more likely to have mental troubles. \r\n   * Luke talked about an IGNobel prize on the subject, but couldn\'t find it here: http://www.improbable.com/ig/winners/#ig2015\r\n* Just finished all works.  Lots of cheques coming in.  Looking for a travel opportunity.  \r\n\r\n\r\nBrennan: has police files, not idea files.  \r\n* Wants to have a telepathy meeting.  \r\n* Also: a workshop on the Soundtrack of your Life.  \r\n\r\nHeidi: Methods for teaching basic to advance consent negotiation skills for 11-13 yo kids.  \r\n* Have been pondering how to do this.  \r\n* Using sex as the example context would be inapropro.  \r\n* This past week came across some ideas:\r\n   * In a dance class, practiced saying no, asking and hearing no.  \r\n   * TED talk about replacing the baseball analogy of sex (first, second base, scoring), but using pizza instead.  \r\n   * We\'re going to order a pizza, and decide what goes on it.  We can all eat it and it\'s inclusive.  \r\n* Kris has been drafting a article called Privacy is Consent.  Counters the two main arguments:\r\n   * Privacy is dead.\r\n   * I have nothing to hide.  \r\n   * Might tie in well to this young group.  \r\n   * Critiqued the Privacy by Design programme.  \r\n   * Luke suggests a \"Privacy by Implementation\" system to counter it.  \r\n* ICM: Integrated Case Management to fuse databases for health and education (among other things).  \r\n* Kris recommended looking up Geoff Williams (sp?) on ideawave on how to incorporate priv&sec into highschool education.  \r\n* Luke commented on what\'s not taught in schools: skepticism, priv&sec, critical thinking, consent etc.  \r\n* Kris talked about the Self-design Learning Centre (http://selfdesign.org/).  They\'re doing quite well, apparently.\r\n* Brennan wants kids to learn about, and how to affirm boundaries.  \r\n* Kris talked about The Game->PUAs->MRAs.  The pickup artist spectrum is broad from the formula to get laid all the way to how to come out of your shell.  \r\n   * Talked about how manipulation has a bad rap.  Talking about how manipulating myself into being likeable is not bad.  \r\n   * Manipulation: control or influence a person or situation cleverly, unfairly or unscrupulously.\r\n   * Luke recommends Heidi read The Game so she can apply it to her education.  \r\n   * Kris recommends most men learn to fake confidence until it becomes natural.  \r\n   * Assertiveness is often correlated with aggressiveness.  \r\n   * \"Nice guys\" often think that jerks get all the ladies, which is often true.  \r\n   * Confidence, assertiveness and independence are the 3 kings of becoming an attractive man.\r\n   * Heidi mentioned a non-profit that teaches assertiveness skills to high school age kids.  The goal is to reduce violence by asserting boundaries.  \r\n   * Social currency problem: if a women asserts boundaries and rejects, it can harm her professional, safety and relationship careers.\r\n   * Related an anecdote from a female friend who got courted, didn\'t respond and got spit on.  \r\n   * Suggested ladies don\'t look girls in the eye.  \r\n   * Let\'s start a \"won\'t call you a cunt\" slogan movement.\r\n* Kris speculates that it\'s not his social network that perpetrates violence against women.  \r\n* Talked about David Ho who is a repeat sexual confinement offender: http://news.nationalpost.com/news/canada/vancouver-billionaire-david-ho-pleads-guilty-to-unlawful-confinement-possession-of-drugs-handgun\r\n* Heidi sits on the pride advisory committee with the VSB.  \r\n* Kris: talked about anecdote of drug fear-mongering in high school.  School education is generally dishonest about the consequences of drug use.  \r\n* Luke talked about one crazy junior-high teacher he had who taught a lot about drugs, including the varying consequences.  \r\n* Talked about date-rape drugs.  Luke advocating for A (Alcohol) being described as date-rape drug and also \"A-holing\".  \r\n* Kris talked about the Colombian blackout drug scopolamine.\r\n* Heidi talked about Wade Davis\' research into developing a technique for making zombies.  \r\n\r\nLuke: Aquaponics gardening concepts and practice.  \r\n\r\nD: Wanted to get feedback on the menus for Roo\'s public house.  One with and without extra-blocked menus.  Consensus was in preference of the more blocky version.  \r\n','Mar 14, 2016','','draft','open','open','','','','','2016-03-15 00:16:31','2016-03-15 04:16:31','',0,'http://www.ideasmeetings.org/?p=54',0,'post','',0),(55,3,'2016-03-15 00:16:31','2016-03-15 04:16:31','Ideas meeting 14 March 2016\r\n\r\nIdeas:\r\n* Aquaponics gardening\r\n\r\nIn attendance:\r\n* Kris\r\n* Brennan (assembling a a caddey \r\n* Heidi Raven\r\n* Luke\r\n\r\nBrennan/Luke idea for Kris: a wire-based art hanger from Ikea\r\n\r\nKris: Honesty in relationships.\r\n* Open to honesty critique about spelling and grammer.\r\n* Just came back from intense meeting with Ex.\r\n* Likeliness of both partners being the same \"place\" is low, so there are expectations.  \r\n* Notion of friendship is broad spectrum: all the way from BFFs to just not hating each other.  \r\n* On the friend spectrum vs. the friend zone.\r\n* How do we solve kind of friends we are?  \r\n   -> Flavour terminology as an analogy towards improving our vocabulary of types of friendships that are possible.  \r\n* Not a good feedback loop for what did and did not work in a relationship.  \r\n* Easier to get feedback from friends, but harder from ex partners.\r\n* Luke suggests exit interviews.  Heidi suggests have feedback meetings more frequently.  \r\n* Focus empathetically on the other partner in a relationship.  \r\n* Heidi implies that positive feedback and affirmation is under-appreciated in arguments and relationship discussions.  Also makes the hard stuff easier to take.  \r\n* Kris spent several years on Facebag as a warrior for technical correctness, but now realizes that most people don\'t want it.  \r\n   * Should there be a badge for who does and who does not want technical correctness.  \r\n   * Heidi suggests asking people what sort of feedback they want.  \r\n* Luke: is non-violent communication what we need?  \r\n   * Kris found it fatiguing, but that was in a poly relationship that had a _lot_ of communication.  \r\n* Kris wants feedback and critique on whatever.  \r\n* What\'s the line?  Where does criticism become misanthropic?  \r\n* Heidi: there are ways to communicate in a caring and helpful/non-misanthropic way?  \r\n* Luke: autism spectrum people have a hard time grasping social queues, and therefore communicating healthily.   \r\n* Aspergers no longer is a diagnosis.\r\n* Night owls are more creative and more likely to have mental troubles. \r\n   * Luke talked about an IGNobel prize on the subject, but couldn\'t find it here: http://www.improbable.com/ig/winners/#ig2015\r\n* Just finished all works.  Lots of cheques coming in.  Looking for a travel opportunity.  \r\n\r\n\r\nBrennan: has police files, not idea files.  \r\n* Wants to have a telepathy meeting.  \r\n* Also: a workshop on the Soundtrack of your Life.  \r\n\r\nHeidi: Methods for teaching basic to advance consent negotiation skills for 11-13 yo kids.  \r\n* Have been pondering how to do this.  \r\n* Using sex as the example context would be inapropro.  \r\n* This past week came across some ideas:\r\n   * In a dance class, practiced saying no, asking and hearing no.  \r\n   * TED talk about replacing the baseball analogy of sex (first, second base, scoring), but using pizza instead.  \r\n   * We\'re going to order a pizza, and decide what goes on it.  We can all eat it and it\'s inclusive.  \r\n* Kris has been drafting a article called Privacy is Consent.  Counters the two main arguments:\r\n   * Privacy is dead.\r\n   * I have nothing to hide.  \r\n   * Might tie in well to this young group.  \r\n   * Critiqued the Privacy by Design programme.  \r\n   * Luke suggests a \"Privacy by Implementation\" system to counter it.  \r\n* ICM: Integrated Case Management to fuse databases for health and education (among other things).  \r\n* Kris recommended looking up Geoff Williams (sp?) on ideawave on how to incorporate priv&sec into highschool education.  \r\n* Luke commente